                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-368-victim1940 t18260914-368-viclabel2068"></join>, who lives in <placeName id="t18260914-368-crimeloc2069">Whitechapel-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-368-crimeloc2069" type="placeName" value="Whitechapel-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-368-crimeloc2069" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-368-off2067 t18260914-368-crimeloc2069"></join>. The prisoner was our <rs id="t18260914-368-deflabel2070" type="occupation">errand-boy</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-368-defend1939 t18260914-368-deflabel2070"></join>, and received money - he should account for it directly. On the <rs id="t18260914-368-cd2071" type="crimeDate">22d of July</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-368-off2067 t18260914-368-cd2071"></join> I sent him to Mrs. Riddle, with goods, and gave him a bill, which amounted to 3l. 19s. 11d. - on his return he paid me 1l. short, and said he was certain it was all that she gave him; I entered it on account. On the Wednesday Mrs. Riddle was at our house; he persisted that it was all she gave him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. BRODRICK. Q. I believe the matter rested two or three days? A. Yes - I think it was a mistake.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-368-person1942">
                  SARAH 
                  RIDDLE
               <interp inst="t18260914-368-person1942" type="surname" value="RIDDLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-368-person1942" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-368-person1942" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I paid the prisoner three sovereigns and 19s.; he wrote a receipt, and put the money into his right-hand pocket; he went for change for sixpence, and when he returned he said I had only given him two sovereigns; I had told him to count it when I paid it him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Was not the money left on the counter while he went for change? A. The silver was - I do not know about the sovereigns; two people were in my shop.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-368-person1943">
                  LUCY 
                  RICKETT
               <interp inst="t18260914-368-person1943" type="surname" value="RICKETT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-368-person1943" type="given" value="LUCY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-368-person1943" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I stood at the counter, and saw Riddle put down three sovereigns; I was called away, and did not see the silver.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Was it not one sovereign and two half-sovereigns? A. No.</p>
               <p>CHARLES WILLIAM GOLDING. He brought me one sovereign and two half-sovereigns.</p>
